ations. Parasites also describes their evolution and life histories and considers their significant benefits. Deftly blending the sociological with the scientific, this natural and social history of parasites looks closely at a fascinating, often disgusting group of organisms and discovers that they are in fact an integral thread in the web of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBiogeography. 0aHost-parasite relationships. 0aParasitesvPopular works. 0aParasitism. 7aNATURE / Animals.2bisacsh  aamoebae.  abiology evolution.  abiology.  acrime scenes.  adisgust.  aeasy to read.  aengaging.  aentomology.  aevolution.  aexploration.  afood and water.  aglobal attitudes.  ahuman cultures.  ahuman history.  ainvaders.  ainvisible life.  aliving tissues.  aman versus nature.  amicrobiology.  amites.  anatural history.  anonfiction.  aorganisms.  aparasites.  aparasitology.  arole of parasites.  aroundworms.  ascience nature.  ascientific.  ascientists.  asocial history.  asociological.  ataboos.  atapeworms.  aterrorism.  athreats and danger.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025938640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094578440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945784/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY